{%- comment -%}
  Product Price — renders price with compare-at and discount badge.
  Birebir from product/[id]/page.tsx price section.

  Accepts:
  - product: {Object} Shopify product
  - variant: {Object} Shopify variant (optional, defaults to selected_or_first_available)
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- liquid
  unless variant
    assign variant = product.selected_or_first_available_variant
  endunless
  assign current_price = variant.price
  assign compare_price = variant.compare_at_price
  # Free product shortcut — show "Free" label in place of $0.00
  # and suppress the sale badge entirely. Without this guard a
  # variant priced at 0 with compare > 0 emits a "-100% OFF" badge
  # over a "$0.00" which reads as broken (sale mechanics against
  # zero are nonsensical — either it's a giveaway or bad data).
  assign is_free = false
  if current_price == 0
    assign is_free = true
  endif
  assign on_sale = false
  if compare_price > current_price and is_free == false
    assign on_sale = true
    assign discount_pct = compare_price | minus: current_price | times: 100 | divided_by: compare_price
  endif
  comment
    When callers render the product's price block without explicitly
    passing `variant` (common on collection/search cards), the price
    can still vary across variants even though we're showing one
    representative price. Flag that so we can prefix with "From" —
    matching Shopify's storefront convention and avoiding customer
    surprise when they land on a PDP to find a higher price than
    the card showed.
  endcomment
  assign show_from_prefix = false
  if variant == product.selected_or_first_available_variant and product.price_varies
    assign show_from_prefix = true
  endif
-%}

<div class="kt-product-price" data-product-price>
  {%- if show_from_prefix -%}
    <span class="kt-product-price__from-label">{{ 'kt.product.from_price_label' | t }}</span>
  {%- endif -%}
  <span class="kt-product-price__current{% if on_sale %} kt-product-price__current--sale{% endif %}">
    {%- if on_sale -%}
      <span class="visually-hidden">{{ 'kt.product.sale_price' | t }}&nbsp;</span>
    {%- endif -%}
    {%- if is_free -%}
      {{ 'kt.cart.free' | t | default: 'Free' }}
    {%- else -%}
      {{ current_price | money }}
    {%- endif -%}
  </span>

  {%- if on_sale -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      Compare-at renders inside <s> so screen readers announce the
      strike-through as a semantic "no-longer-valid price". A CSS
      text-decoration alone doesn't convey the meaning to AT.
      Visually-hidden prefix gives the reader the label, so AT
      reads "Regular price $80, sale price $60" instead of "80 60".
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <s class="kt-product-price__compare">
      <span class="visually-hidden">{{ 'kt.product.regular_price' | t }}&nbsp;</span>
      {{ compare_price | money }}
    </s>
    <span class="kt-product-price__discount">
      -{{ discount_pct }}%
    </span>
  {%- endif -%}

  {%- comment -%}
    Unit pricing — mandatory in the EU for consumables sold by weight
    or volume (e.g. \u20AC3.99 per 100 g). Shopify populates
    `variant.unit_price` only when the merchant sets a reference value
    on the variant, so this block renders nothing on a store that
    doesn't need it. Format mirrors Shopify's own reference example:
    unit price + reference unit, with the measured quantity disclosed
    in parentheses when it differs from the reference quantity
    (e.g. \"250 g per 1 kg\"), which is what German price-transparency
    law requires.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- if variant.unit_price_measurement -%}
    {%- assign upm = variant.unit_price_measurement -%}
    <span class="kt-product-price__unit" data-unit-price>
      <span class="kt-product-price__unit-value">{{ variant.unit_price | money }}</span>
      <span class="kt-product-price__unit-separator" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span class="kt-product-price__unit-ref">
        {%- if upm.reference_value != 1 -%}
          {{ upm.reference_value }}&nbsp;
        {%- endif -%}
        {{ upm.reference_unit }}
      </span>
      {%- if upm.quantity_value != upm.reference_value -%}
        <span class="kt-product-price__unit-qty">
          ({{ 'kt.product.unit_price_per_html' | t: quantity_value: upm.quantity_value, quantity_unit: upm.quantity_unit, reference_value: upm.reference_value, reference_unit: upm.reference_unit }})
        </span>
      {%- endif -%}
    </span>
  {%- endif -%}

  {%- comment -%}
    Tax-inclusive indicator — Theme Store mandatory: "tax-inclusive
    indication using cart.taxes_included". When a merchant operates in
    a jurisdiction that displays prices INCLUDING tax (most EU stores),
    the storefront must label the displayed price as such so customers
    aren't surprised by an unchanged total at checkout. We mirror the
    pattern already used in main-cart.liquid + cart-drawer.liquid for
    consistency between PDP, cart drawer, and cart page.

    `cart.taxes_included` is true when Shopify Admin's "All prices
    include tax" toggle is on; it's false in tax-exclusive markets
    (e.g. US default), which renders this block as nothing — no
    misleading "Tax included" label on a price that doesn't actually
    include tax.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- if cart.taxes_included -%}
    <span class="kt-product-price__tax-note">
      {{ 'kt.product.taxes_included' | t | default: 'Tax included.' }}
    </span>
  {%- endif -%}
</div>
